{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"df6ce46e-054d-4020-80ce-c940f7b8db70","content":"Here's the correct attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute |\n|-----------|-----------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` or `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` |\n\n**Example usage:**\n\n```csharp\n// MSTest\n[TestMethod]\n[Ignore(\"Waiting on bug fix #1234\")]\npublic void MyMsTest() { }\n\n// xUnit\n[Fact(Skip = \"Waiting on bug fix #1234\")]\npublic void MyXunitTest() { }\n\n// NUnit\n[Test]\n[Ignore(\"Waiting on bug fix #1234\")]\npublic void MyNunitTest() { }\n\n// TUnit\n[Test]\n[Skip(\"Waiting on bug fix #1234\")]\npublic void MyTunitTest() { }\n```\n\n> **Note:** In xUnit, `Skip` is a property on the test attribute itself, not a separate attribute. For NUnit and MSTest, `[Ignore]` is placed alongside the test attribute.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"532fcf9d-dcf5-435c-8a9a-e6af04f440e0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about test-skipping attributes across four .NET test frameworks. This is a knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":330,"requestId":"981A:180764:1AB704:22FAEC:69FFDC0D"},"id":"2d87b2f0-97e9-46cd-b1bd-a2970c09b505","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:15:00.310Z","parentId":"b5edc1ea-b9c8-431d-a45e-91e237e47f7c"}
